Example using let:

```
function exampleFunction() {
  let x = 5;
  if (true) {
    let x = 10;
    console.log(x); // Output: 10, block-level scope
  }
  console.log(x); // Output: 5, function-level scope
}
```

In this example, we use let to declare a variable x with block-level scope. We then declare another variable with the same name inside an if block, but because it is also using let, it is a different variable with a different scope that does not affect the value of the first x variable outside of the if block. This helps prevent unintentional variable shadowing and bugs.

Example using var:

```
function exampleFunction() {
  var x = 5;
  if (true) {
    var x = 10;
    console.log(x); // Output: 10, same variable is used
  }
  console.log(x); // Output: 10, overwritten by above block
}
```

In this example, we use var to declare a variable x with function-level scope. We then declare another variable with the same name inside an if block, but because it is using var, it overwrites the first x variable due to hoisting. This can cause unintentional bugs and make the code harder to understand and maintain.
